## üß† UX PRINCIPLES (STATE OF THE ART)

Good design isn't just visual ‚Äî it must be usable, accessible, and feel responsive. These principles are mandatory for every feature.

---

### 1. FEEDBACK & STATE MANAGEMENT

**Every action needs visible feedback.** Users should never wonder "did that work?"

**Required States for Interactive Elements:**
```
‚ñ° Default ‚Äî Normal appearance
‚ñ° Hover ‚Äî Visual change on mouse over
‚ñ° Active/Pressed ‚Äî Feedback during click
‚ñ° Loading ‚Äî Show something is happening
‚ñ° Success ‚Äî Confirm the action worked
‚ñ° Error ‚Äî Explain what went wrong
‚ñ° Disabled ‚Äî Clearly show it's not available
```

**Loading States (Never leave users hanging):**
```css
/* Skeleton loader for content */
.skeleton {
  background: linear-gradient(
    90deg,
    var(--bg-secondary) 25%,
    var(--bg-elevated) 50%,
    var(--bg-secondary) 75%
  );
  background-size: 200% 100%;
  animation: shimmer 1.5s infinite;
  border-radius: 4px;
}

@keyframes shimmer {
  0% { background-position: 200% 0; }
  100% { background-position: -200% 0; }
}

/* Button loading state */
.btn-loading {
  position: relative;
  color: transparent;
  pointer-events: none;
}

.btn-loading::after {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  width: 16px;
  height: 16px;
  border: 2px solid transparent;
  border-top-color: currentColor;
  border-radius: 50%;
  animation: spin 0.6s linear infinite;
}

@keyframes spin {
  to { transform: rotate(360deg); }
}
```

**Rules:**
- Show loading state immediately (within 100ms of action)
- Use skeleton loaders for content, spinners for actions
- Optimistic updates where safe (show success, rollback on failure)
- Never block the entire UI ‚Äî load progressively

---

### 2. EMPTY STATES & ZERO DATA

**Empty states are opportunities, not dead ends.**

**Every empty state must include:**
1. What this area is for (context)
2. Why it's empty (explanation)
3. What to do next (clear CTA)

**Example:**
```jsx
// ‚ùå Bad empty state
<div>No items</div>

// ‚úÖ Good empty state
<div className="empty-state">
  <Icon name="inbox" />
  <h3>No messages yet</h3>
  <p>When you receive messages, they'll appear here.</p>
  <Button>Send your first message</Button>
</div>
```

**Empty State Checklist:**
```
‚ñ° Friendly, helpful tone (not "Error: No data")
‚ñ° Visual element (icon or illustration)
‚ñ° Brief explanation
‚ñ° Primary action to resolve the empty state
‚ñ° Consistent styling with the rest of the app
```

---

### 3. ERROR HANDLING & RECOVERY

**Errors are inevitable. Good UX makes recovery easy.**

**Error Message Formula:**
```
What happened + Why it happened + How to fix it
```

**Examples:**
```
‚ùå "Error 500"
‚úÖ "Couldn't save your changes. The server is temporarily unavailable. Your work has been saved locally ‚Äî try again in a few minutes."

‚ùå "Invalid input"
‚úÖ "Email address needs an @ symbol. Example: name@email.com"

‚ùå "Failed"
‚úÖ "Couldn't connect to your account. Check your internet connection and try again."
```

**Error Placement:**
- Form errors: Inline, next to the field (not just at the top)
- Action errors: Toast/snackbar that doesn't block the UI
- Critical errors: Modal with clear recovery path

**Error Styling:**
```css
.error-message {
  color: #DC2626;
  font-size: 0.875rem;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 0.5rem;
  margin-top: 0.5rem;
}

/* Error state for inputs */
.input-error {
  border-color: #DC2626;
  background: #FEF2F2;
}

.input-error:focus {
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(220, 38, 38, 0.1);
}
```

**Rules:**
- Never use technical jargon in user-facing errors
- Always provide a way forward (retry, alternative, support)
- Preserve user input on errors (don't clear forms)
- Log detailed errors to console for debugging

