### 6. ACCESSIBILITY (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

**Accessibility is not optional. These are baseline requirements.**

**Minimum Requirements:**
```
‚ñ° Color contrast ratio 4.5:1 for text (use WebAIM checker)
‚ñ° All interactive elements keyboard accessible
‚ñ° Focus states visible (never `outline: none` without replacement)
‚ñ° Images have alt text
‚ñ° Form inputs have labels
‚ñ° Errors announced to screen readers (role="alert")
‚ñ° Touch targets minimum 44x44px on mobile
‚ñ° No information conveyed by color alone
```

**Focus Styles:**
```css
/* Never do this */
*:focus { outline: none; } /* ‚ùå Hides focus for keyboard users */

/* Do this instead */
*:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--accent);
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

/* Remove focus ring for mouse users only */
*:focus:not(:focus-visible) {
  outline: none;
}
```

**ARIA When Needed:**
```jsx
// Loading state
<button aria-busy="true" aria-label="Saving...">
  <Spinner />
</button>

// Error announcement
<div role="alert" aria-live="polite">
  {errorMessage}
</div>

// Icon-only button
<button aria-label="Close menu">
  <IconX />
</button>
```

**Testing Accessibility:**
- Tab through the entire page ‚Äî can you reach everything?
- Use the app with screen reader (VoiceOver on Mac: Cmd+F5)
- Test at 200% zoom ‚Äî does layout break?

---

### 7. RESPONSIVE & MOBILE UX

**Design mobile-first, then enhance for desktop.**

**Touch Target Sizes:**
```css
/* Minimum touch target */
.touchable {
  min-height: 44px;
  min-width: 44px;
  padding: 12px;
}

/* Spacing between touch targets */
.button-group {
  gap: 8px; /* Minimum 8px between targets */
}
```

**Mobile Navigation Patterns:**
- Bottom navigation for primary actions (thumb zone)
- Hamburger menu for secondary navigation
- Pull-to-refresh for content feeds
- Swipe gestures with visual affordance

**Responsive Breakpoints:**
```css
/* Mobile first */
.container { padding: 1rem; }

/* Tablet */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container { padding: 2rem; }
}

/* Desktop */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container { padding: 3rem; max-width: 1200px; }
}
```

**Rules:**
- Test on real devices, not just browser resize
- Critical actions always visible (no hidden menus)
- Forms work with mobile keyboards (proper input types)
- Images and media are responsive

---

### 8. PERFORMANCE PERCEPTION

**Perceived speed matters more than actual speed.**

**Techniques:**
```
‚ñ° Skeleton loaders instead of spinners for content
‚ñ° Optimistic updates (show success immediately, rollback on failure)
‚ñ° Progressive loading (show content as it arrives)
‚ñ° Preload likely next actions
‚ñ° Instant feedback on user input (<100ms)
```

**Response Time Guidelines:**
```
< 100ms   ‚Üí Feels instant (button feedback)
< 300ms   ‚Üí Feels fast (page transitions)
< 1000ms  ‚Üí Maintain attention (show progress)
> 1000ms  ‚Üí Explain what's happening (loading state)
> 10000s  ‚Üí Allow user to do other things
```

**Code Example:**
```jsx
// Optimistic update
const handleLike = async () => {
  setLiked(true); // Immediately show liked state
  setCount(c => c + 1);
  
  try {
    await api.like(postId);
  } catch {
    setLiked(false); // Rollback on failure
    setCount(c => c - 1);
    showError("Couldn't save. Try again.");
  }
};
```

---

### 9. COGNITIVE LOAD REDUCTION

**Don't make users think. Reduce decisions and complexity.**

**Principles:**
```
‚ñ° One primary action per screen (clear CTA)
‚ñ° Progressive disclosure (show more only when needed)
‚ñ° Sensible defaults (pre-select the common choice)
‚ñ° Chunking (group related items, max 5-7 items per group)
‚ñ° Recognition over recall (show options, don't require memory)
```

**Choice Reduction:**
```jsx
// ‚ùå Too many equal options
<div>
  <Button>Save</Button>
  <Button>Save and Close</Button>
  <Button>Save as Draft</Button>
  <Button>Save and New</Button>
</div>

// ‚úÖ Clear hierarchy
<div>
  <Button variant="primary">Save</Button>
  <Button variant="ghost">Save as Draft</Button>
</div>
```

**Progressive Disclosure:**
- Show essential options first
- "Advanced options" or "More settings" for power users
- Expand/collapse for long content
- Step-by-step wizards for complex tasks

---

### 10. CONFIRMATION & DESTRUCTIVE ACTIONS

**Protect users from mistakes, especially irreversible ones.**

**When to Confirm:**
```
‚ñ° Deleting data
‚ñ° Canceling in-progress work
‚ñ° Sending/publishing (can't unsend)
‚ñ° Actions affecting other users
‚ñ° Irreversible changes
```

**Confirmation Dialog Pattern:**
```jsx
// Destructive confirmation
<Dialog>
  <h3>Delete this project?</h3>
  <p>
    "Project Name" and all its contents will be permanently deleted. 
    This action cannot be undone.
  </p>
  <div className="dialog-actions">
    <Button variant="ghost">Cancel</Button>
    <Button variant="destructive">Delete Project</Button>
  </div>
</Dialog>
```

**Rules:**
- Destructive button should say what it does ("Delete Project" not "Yes")
- Include the name of what's being deleted
- Primary action should NOT be the destructive one (make Cancel more prominent)
- Offer undo instead of confirmation when possible (less disruptive)

**Undo Pattern (Preferred):**
```jsx
// Better than confirmation dialog
<Toast>
  <span>Project deleted</span>
  <Button onClick={undo}>Undo</Button>
</Toast>
```

